 that the genre should be understood as a backlash against feminism and a relapse into sexism. By applying an eclectic theoretical framework, ranging from Raymond Williams to Anthony Giddens, Judith Butler and Jacques Derrida, the study illustrates why the male confessional novel is too complex a phenomenon to be solely interpreted in terms of retrosexism. It convincingly shows how the multitude of postmodern gender scripts adds to the crisis of identity and to the problematic nature of clearly defined gender relationships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConfession stories, Englishy20th centuryxCriticism and interpretation. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aBritish Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aDeconstruction. 4aGender Studies. 4aGender Trouble. 4aGender. 4aIdentity Crisis. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aMasculinity. 4aPerformativity. 4aPopular Culture. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBritish Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aDeconstruction.  aGender Studies.  aGender Trouble.  aGender.  aIdentity Crisis.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aMasculinity.  aPerformativity.  aPopular Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Backlist eBook Package 2000-2013z978311102523008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript English Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066155208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Highlight Collection Complete Package 2000-2009z9783110463415oZDB-23-TSO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Highlight Collection Lit. & Kultur 2000-2009z97831104634080 cprintz978383761161840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839411612?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978383941161242